The soundtrack for the arcade version was composed by Ayako Mori.<ref>{{Cite web |title=森安也子 - みんなで決めるゲーム音楽ベスト100まとめwiki【7/16更新】 |url=https://w.atwiki.jp/gamemusicbest100/pages/3811.html |access-date=2023-07-22 |website=森安也子 - みんなで決めるゲーム音楽ベスト100まとめwiki |language=ja}}</ref> On August 25, 1986, [[Alfa Records]] released a limited-edition soundtrack, featuring all of the music from the arcade version, as well as two unused tracks. Its catalog number was Capcom Game Music – 28XA-94.

== Reception ==
''Game Machine'' listed ''Gun.Smoke'' in their January 1986 issue as being the second most-successful table arcade unit of the month in Japan.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Game Machine's Best Hit Games 25 - テーブル型TVゲーム機 (Table Videos)|magazine=[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]]|issue=275|publisher=[[:ja:アミューズメント通信社|Amusement Press, Inc.]]|date=1 January 1986|page=35|lang=ja}}</ref> The US ''[[Play Meter]]'' charts listed it as one of the top five arcade games the same month.<ref>{{cite journal |title=National Play Meter |journal=[[Play Meter]] |date=January 15, 1986 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=20–1 |url=https://archive.org/details/play-meter-volume-12-number-1-january-15th-1986-600DPI/Play%20Meter%20-%20Volume%2012%2C%20Number%201%20-%20January%2015th%201986%20%28Compressed%29/page/20}}</ref> It went on to be Japan's sixth highest-grossing table arcade game during the [[1986 in video games|first half of 1986]].<ref name="GM288">{{cite magazine |title=Game Machine's Best Hit Games 25: '86 上半期 |trans-title=Game Machine's Best Hit Games 25: First Half '86 |magazine=[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]] |issue=288 |publisher=[[:ja:アミューズメント通信社|Amusement Press, Inc.]] |date=15 July 1986 |page=28 |lang=ja |url=https://onitama.tv/gamemachine/pdf/19860715p.pdf#page=15}}</ref>

The arcade game received positive reviews. In a January 1986 issue of ''[[Play Meter]]'' magazine, Frank Seninsky listed ''Gun.Smoke'' as the top recommended arcade conversion kit, calling it "a number-one kit with great graphics."<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Seninsky |first1=Frank |title=Frank's Cranks: Systems/Trivias/Conversions (Part II) |magazine=[[Play Meter]] |date=January 15, 1986 |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=28–30 |url=https://archive.org/details/play-meter-volume-12-number-1-january-15th-1986-600DPI/Play%20Meter%20-%20Volume%2012%2C%20Number%201%20-%20January%2015th%201986/page/28/mode/2up}}</ref> ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' magazine gave the arcade game a positive review in March 1986, calling it an "excellent" fast-paced shooter, considering it to be better than [[light gun shooter]]s such as ''[[Hogan's Alley (video game)|Hogan's Alley]]'' and ''[[Shoot Out]]''.<ref name="CVG"/>

== Sequel ==
A sequel, titled ''Desperado 2'', was developed by [[Topo Soft]] and released in 1991. The game was released on [[Amstrad CPC]], [[MS-DOS]], [[MSX]], and [[ZX Spectrum]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Desperado 2 (1991) |url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/desperado-2 |access-date=2022-09-26 |website=MobyGames}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=GAMART s.c.p |title=Desperado 2 |date=1991 |url=http://archive.org/details/msdos_Desperado_2_1991 |access-date=2022-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Desperado 2 at Spectrum Computing - Sinclair ZX Spectrum games, software and hardware |url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/entry/1361/ZX-Spectrum/Desperado_2 |access-date=2022-09-26 |website=Spectrum Computing |language=en}}</ref>

